{"cursor":"47058","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\ns (ice crystals) by Wilson Bentley, 1902]]\n\n'Ice' is water frozen into the solid state. It can appear transparent or opaque\nbluish-white color, depending on the presence of impurities or air inclusions.\nThe addition of other materials such as soil may further alter the appearance.\n\nIce appears in nature in forms of snowflakes, hail, icicles, ice spikes and\ncandles, glaciers, pack ice, frost, and entire polar ice caps. It is an\nimportant component of the global climate, and plays an important role in the\nwater cycle. Furthermore, ice has numerous cultural applications, from ice\ncooling of drinks to winter sports and the art of ice sculpting.\n\nThe molecules in solid ice may be arranged in different ways, called phases,\ndepending on the temperature and pressure. Usually ice is the phase known as ice\nI h, which is the most abundant of the varying solid phases on the\nEarth's surface. The most common phase transition to ice I h occurs\nwhen liquid water is cooled below (, ) at standard atmospheric pressure. It can\nalso deposit from vapour with no intervening liquid phase, such as in the\nformation of frost.\n\nThe word is derived from Old English Ä«s, which in turn stems from Proto-\nGermanic [[isaz]].\n","linknr":891,"url":"Ice","recorded":1362372212,"links":154,"instances":["physics","sport","commerce","town","chemistry","unit","matter","building","geology","crystal_system","meteorology"],"pdf":["http://lptms.u-psud.fr/membres/trizac/Ens/L3FIP/Ice.pdf","http://lptms.u-psud.fr/membres/trizac/Ens/L3FIP/Ice.pdf","http://www.spc.noaa.gov/publications/jewell/hailslsc.pdf","http://www.spc.noaa.gov/publications/jewell/hailslsc.pdf","http://www.census.gov/prod/ec02/ec0231i312113.pdf","http://militzer.berkeley.edu/papers/ice26.pdf","http://militzer.berkeley.edu/papers/ice26.pdf","http://arxiv.org/pdf/1106.1941.pdf","http://arxiv.org/pdf/1106.1941.pdf","https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/id/1183